Atomic types and classes

Factors

R uses factors to represent categorical variables. Factor consists of:

  1. A set of values
  2. A set of valid levels

Factors are stored as an integer value with a levels attribute

a <- c(1,1,3,2,3,1)
factor(a)
factor(a,labels=c("blue","brown","green"))

eyes <- factor(x = c("blue", "green", "green"), 
          levels = c("blue", "brown", "green"))

Which religions watch the least TV

gss_cat %>%
  filter(!is.na(tvhours)) %>%
  group_by(relig) %>%
  summarize(tvhours = mean(tvhours)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(tvhours, relig)) +
    geom_point()

Which religions watch the least TV

fct_reorder

Reorders the levels of a factor based on the result of fun(x) applied to each group of cases (grouped by level)

fct_reorder

gss_cat %>%
  filter(!is.na(tvhours)) %>%
  group_by(relig) %>%
  summarize(tvhours = mean(tvhours)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(tvhours, fct_reorder(relig, tvhours,.fun = mean))) +
    geom_point()

fct_recode()

Compute the average tv hours by party ID and then plot the results

gss_cat %>%
   filter(!is.na(tvhours)) %>%
   group_by(partyid) %>%
   summarise(tvhours = mean(tvhours)) %>%
   ggplot(aes(tvhours, fct_reorder(partyid, tvhours))) +
     geom_point() +
     labs(y = "partyid")

fct_recode()

Compute the average tv hours by party ID and then plot the results

fct_recode()

fct_recode()

gss_cat %>%
   filter(!is.na(tvhours)) %>%
    mutate(partyid = fct_recode(partyid,
    "Republican, strong"    = "Strong republican",
    "Republican, weak"      = "Not str republican",
    "Independent, near rep" = "Ind,near rep",
    "Independent, near dem" = "Ind,near dem",
    "Democrat, weak"        = "Not str democrat",
    "Democrat, strong"      = "Strong democrat")) %>% 
   group_by(partyid) %>%
   summarize(tvhours = mean(tvhours)) %>%
   ggplot(aes(tvhours, fct_reorder(partyid, tvhours))) +
     geom_point() + labs(y = "partyid")

fct_collapse()

gss_cat %>%
   filter(!is.na(tvhours)) %>%
    mutate(partyid = fct_collapse(partyid,
      "conservative" = c("Strong republican", 
                       "Not str republican", 
                       "Ind,near rep"),
      "liberal" = c("Strong democrat", 
                  "Not str democrat", 
                  "Ind,near dem"))) %>% 
   group_by(partyid) %>%
   summarize(tvhours = mean(tvhours)) %>%
   ggplot(aes(tvhours, fct_reorder(partyid, tvhours))) +
     geom_point() + labs(y = "partyid")

Classes for time

R’s classes for time:

  1. POSIXct. Stored as the number of seconds since 1970-01-01
  2. Dates. Stored as the number of days since 1970-01-01

Date time

Sys.time()
## [1] "2022-11-29 14:21:12 EST"
unclass(Sys.time())
## [1] 1669749673
Sys.Date()
## [1] "2022-11-29"
unclass(Sys.Date())
## [1] 19325

What is the best day of the week to fly?

Load the package library(lubridate)

To parse strings as dates, use the function whose name is y, m, d, h, m, s in the correct order.

ymd("2012/01/11")
mdy("January 11 2012")
ymd_hms("2012-01-11  01:30:55")

Extract components by name with a singular name

date <- ymd("2019-01-11")
year(date)
## [1] 2019
year(date) <- 1999
date
## [1] "1999-01-11"

Lubridate

wday(ymd("2019-01-11"))
## [1] 6
wday(ymd("2019-01-11"), label = TRUE)
## [1] Fri
## Levels: Sun < Mon < Tue < Wed < Thu < Fri < Sat
wday(ymd("2019-01-11"), label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE)
## [1] Friday
## 7 Levels: Sunday < Monday < Tuesday < Wednesday < Thursday < ... < Saturday
